<subSubSection pageId="52" pageNumber="53" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="52.[189,324,1621,1647]" box="[189,324,1621,1647]" pageId="52" pageNumber="53">
<heading bold="true" box="[189,324,1621,1647]" fontSize="11" level="3" pageId="52" pageNumber="53" reason="3">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[189,324,1621,1647]" pageId="52" pageNumber="53">Etymology</emphasis>
</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="52.[189,1399,1667,1834]" pageId="52" pageNumber="53">
The species name is derived from the acronym for the Asociación para la Conservación de la Cuenca Amazónica (ACCA) because most of the 
<typeStatus box="[676,727,1703,1729]" pageId="52" pageNumber="53">type</typeStatus>
specimens are from the ACCA field station at Wayqecha. This is also a welcome opportunity to honour an organization that has done so much to protect Peruvian biodiversity and to facilitate documentation of that biodiversity while training the next generation of Amazonian conservationists.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
